e Waters, 1900–2000 -- t20 Conclusion: Historical Legacies and Present Concerns -- tBibliography -- tThe Contributors -- tIndex -- tAbout the Book0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIntercultural relations have revolved around the River Nile throughout recorded history: sharing the river's waters, Egyptians, Ethiopians, and Sudanese have developed rich dialogues of mutual cultural enrichment, as well as misconceptions and conflicts. This volume represents a rigorous scholarly attempt to trace these complex relations, exploring the multifaceted representations of the Nile, both in the region and in the West, from early medieval times to the present. Underlying the authors’ analysis is their recognition that the resurgent nationalism and sociopolitical revolutions of the present century have aggravated historical conflicts and often reinvented traditional images. Their hope is that reconstructing the continuum of the Nile's history, its changes, and its cultural reciprocity will enhance mutual understanding as the regional faces the acute water problems predicted for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aAbdalla, Ismail H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArbel, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyalon, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Robert O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirar, Uoldelul Chelati, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonze, Emery van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErlich, Haggai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/